    <div class="card">
      <h2>Comprehensive Guide</h2>
      <p>Turmeric is renowned for its vibrant yellow color and earthy, slightly bitter, mustard-like flavor. It is a staple in curries and has gained popularity for its active compound, curcumin.</p>
    <h3>Fresh vs Dried</h3>
    <p>Fresh turmeric looks similar to ginger root but with a bright orange interior. It has a brighter, slightly more citrusy flavor than the dried powder. Dried turmeric is earthier and highly concentrated.</p>
    <h3>Health Claims vs Evidence</h3>
    <p>Curcumin is studied for its anti-inflammatory properties, but it has very low bioavailability on its own. Pairing turmeric with black pepper (piperine) increases its absorption by up to 2000%. Cooking it in a fat (like coconut oil or ghee) also helps the body absorb the fat-soluble curcumin.</p>
    <h3>Pairings</h3>
    <p>Turmeric pairs exceptionally well with ginger, cumin, coriander, and garlic. It is frequently used to color rice dishes and is a base ingredient in most curry powders.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <h3>How do I get turmeric stains out of my counters?</h3><p>Make a paste of baking soda and water, apply it to the stain, let it sit for 15 minutes, and gently scrub. Lemon juice or white vinegar can also help bleach the stain.</p><h3>Is fresh turmeric better than dried?</h3><p>They have different applications. Fresh turmeric has a brighter flavor, while dried is earthier. Use a 3:1 ratio of fresh to dried if substituting.</p><h3>What is golden milk?</h3><p>Golden milk is a traditional Indian drink made by simmering milk with turmeric, black pepper, cinnamon, ginger, and a sweetener.</p>
